  "prompt": "Why does a salt solution conduct electricity?",
  "response": "A salt solution conducts electricity because the salt (typically sodium chloride, NaCl) dissociates into its constituent ions when dissolved in water. In the case of sodium chloride, it separates into positively charged sodium ions (Na\u207a) and negatively charged chloride ions (Cl\u207b). These free ions are mobile in the aqueous solution and can carry an electric charge, allowing the solution to conduct electricity.\n\nIn an electric field, the positive sodium ions move toward the negative electrode (cathode), and the negative chloride ions move toward the positive electrode (anode). This movement of ions constitutes an electric current. Thus, the presence of these free ions in the solution facilitates the conduction of electricity.",
